<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06020002 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06020002 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  POLITICS; LODGING; FACILITY; TRAVEL; RANKING  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  WHAT do politicians want in their hotel rooms?;    Hold the jokes, now. Thisis serious.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  POLITICIANS RATE HOTEL AMENITIES  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     LODGING, the management magazine of the American Hotel andamp; Motel Association,asked 22 of what it calls &quot;the ultimate frequent travelers&quot; -- politicians --what they most like in a hotel.;    For the record, nothing illicit or illegalwas cited.;    Fax machines and room service topped the list of preferences.Gov. Norman H. Bangerter of Utah specifies he and his wife both enjoy roomservice.;    Newspapers, swimming pools and cable TV tied for second.;    Rep.Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee,likes to relax with ESPN, the sports channel, while Rep. Tim Johnson, D-S.D.,likes the whole range -- CNN to VH1 -- in a room that is &quot;clean, updated andinexpensive. I don't want a seedy carpet and mold in the shower.&quot; (Obviously apolitician of high standards.);    Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., is another cleanpolitician -- he likes a hotel with good, strong water pressure in theshower.;    Hartford (Conn.) Mayor Carrie Saxon Perry isn't afraid of a littlework -- while room service is her favorite amenity, she also insists on aniron and full-size ironing board.;    Douglas Wilder and William DonaldSchaefer, Democratic governors of Virginia and Maryland, respectively, bothlike peace, quiet and privacy -- specifically, says Wilder, hotel employeesthat are not overbearing (strong words for a politician).;    Gary Shaeffer,mayor of Cheyenne, Wyo., likes a hotel with a restaurant that serves &quot;good,wholesome food.&quot;;    Gov. Guy Hunt, R-Ala., is happy to find fruit in hisroom.;    And Nevada Gov. Bob Miller, a Democrat, looks for affordability,hospitality and variety. The last, he points out, can be found in Nevadahotels, which feature shopping, casinos, restaurants and entertainment.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  SOPHIA DEMBLING, Dallas Morning News  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910120  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4T  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  292  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday January 20, 199100020002,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>